english:
  title: In Response to the Rhymes of the Wu Envoy at Lin Pan Station
  author: Im Yu-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Wherever I go becomes my home, yet sorrow I cannot escape—
    Even in my prime, my temples already silver with autumn's surprise.
    Beneath the Azure Dragon Gate, I long for my sovereign,
    Within the White Jade Capital, I dream of pleasures past.
    The terraced halls that press down on earth speak of spring's wealth and rank,
    While cups raised in jest and laughter taste of drunken grace.
    Once parted, there is no way to return again—
    As the setting sun calls me to leave, I linger still a moment more.
  footnotes:
    - The Azure Dragon Gate (蒼龍闕) refers to the imperial palace or court.
    - The White Jade Capital (白玉京) is a classical allusion to an idealized celestial or imperial realm.
    - This poem is composed of couplets, each attributed to different classical Chinese poets, a common literary game of the period.
